{{nihongo|'''Nomi no Sukune''' or '''Nomino Sukune'''|野見 宿禰}} was a Japanese legendary [[sumo]] wrestler during the [[Emperor Suinin]] era.<ref name="katano">{{cite web|url=http://www12.ocn.ne.jp/~katano/e-yuisyo.html |title=The history of Kitano Jinja |publisher=Kitano Jinja |accessdate=2008-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219104915/http://www12.ocn.ne.jp/~katano/e-yuisyo.html |archivedate=February 19, 2008 }}</ref> Allegedly, in 23 B.C., the Emperor instructed Nomi no Sukune to deal with {{nihongo|Taima no Kehaya|当麻蹴速}} after he  boasted that he was the strongest man "under the heavens." Nomi no Sukune engaged Taima no Kuyahaya in hand-to-hand combat and broke his ribs with one kick and his back with another, killing Taima no Kehaya.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Guttmann|first1=Allen|last2=Thompson|first2=Lee|title=Japanese Sports: A History|url=https://archive.org/details/japanesesportshi00gutt|url-access=limited|date=2001|publisher=University of Hawai'i Press|location=Honolulu, HI|isbn=9780824824143|page=[https://archive.org/details/japanesesportshi00gutt/page/n24 14]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essortment.com/wrestlingsumoh_rvqp.htm|title=Sumo wrestling history, the Ancient Japanese sport|publisher=Essortment|accessdate=2008-02-19}}</ref>  It was not modern sumo, but he is regarded as the human creator of sumo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinatownconnection.com/sumo-wrestling-history.htm|title=History of Sumo Wrestling|publisher=Houston Chinatown|accessdate=2008-02-19}}</ref><!--  He is also regarded as the human creator of [[jujutsu]].<ref name="aikido">{{cite web|url=http://www.aikido-shobukan.org/books/View.aspx?id=330|title=Canon of Judo "Principle and Technique"|author=Mifune, Kiyuzo|work=Aikido Shobukan Dojo|date=1959|accessdate=2008-02-19}}</ref> --> He was an ancestor of [[Sugawara no Michizane]],<ref name="katano" /> great-grandfather to Haji no Mino and was the founder of the Haji Clan after his creation of ''[[haniwa]].''<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nomi no Sukune • A History of Japan - 日本歴史|url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/nomi-no-sukune/|access-date=2021-09-01|website=A History of Japan - 日本歴史|language=en-GB}}</ref>

A mural of him, removed from the old [[National Olympic Stadium (Tokyo)|National Olympic Stadium]] in 2014, will be put on display at the new stadium in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=東京五輪向け壁画取り外し…建て替え国立競技場|url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/olympic/2020/20141105-OYT1T50114.html?from=ycont_top_txt|accessdate=8 November 2014|work=Yomiuri Shinbun|date=5 November 2014}}</ref>

